Since Foot wrote in the 1960s, cognitive psychologists have investigated why people respond as they do to ethical dilemmas. \citet{waldmann:2012_moral} summarize factors found to influence judgements, including:
- whether an agent is part of the danger (e.g., on the trolley) or a bystander;
- whether an action involves forceful contact with a victim;
- whether an action targets an object (like a switch) or the victim directly;
- how directly the victim’s suffering impinges on the agent (e.g., informational directness);
- how the victim is described.
They conclude: 'A brief summary of the research of the past years is that it has been shown that almost all these confounding factors influence judgments, along with a number of others' \citep[p. 288]{waldmann:2012_moral}.

Philosophers' moral judgements have been shown to be susceptible to various framing effects, including:
- Order-of-presentation effects \citep{schwitzgebel:2015_philosophers}
- The presence of additional irrelevant options influencing choices between relevant ones \citep{wiegmann:2020_intuitivea}
- 'Asian disease' style framing (presenting outcomes as gains vs. losses) \citep{wiegmann:2020_intuitive, tversky:1981_framing}
